The DMDC equation is based on a theoretical framework that incorporates elements of modified gravity, scalar-tensor theories, and quantum gravity. The underlying assumption is that dark matter is not a particle, but rather a manifestation of the gravitational field.
*Modified Gravity*
The DMDC equation modifies the standard Poisson equation of gravity by introducing a dynamic term that depends on the local density and velocity fields. This modification allows for a more nuanced understanding of gravitational interactions on small scales.
*Scalar-Tensor Theories*
The DMDC equation incorporates elements of scalar-tensor theories, which postulate the existence of a scalar field that couples to the gravitational field. This scalar field can affect the evolution of the universe on large scales.
*Quantum Gravity*
The DMDC equation also incorporates elements of quantum gravity, which seeks to merge quantum mechanics and general relativity. The dynamic term in the DMDC equation can be seen as a manifestation of quantum gravitational effects on small scales.
